<page_title>Amorphization under pressure</page_title>
<text>Amorphization under pressure
p. 5 of 7

&lt; Previous | Index | Next &gt;

If there is no other polymorph that has a tighter compaction, a loosely-packed molecular crystal may be turned into an amorphous (without any shape) solid by applying pressure. 

Like the denaturation of a protein, sometimes a loss of structure is a good thing and sometimes it is not desirable. Amorphous solids like glass and plastic behave differently from crystalline solids. This is very important in drug making. 

Why do manufacturers want to develop many of their drugs as crystals?  &quot;When making a drug in solution, the drug is added to the other chemicals to prolong its shelf life. When the drug is crystallizing, if it forms a crystalline solid, there is space in the crystal for the ice to come out leaving the drug and the components. This process only takes about two or three days. If the drug forms an amorphous solid during the crystallizing phase then, it takes about seven days. This is because amorphous solids do not have space for the ice to come out during the freezing;  therefore the ice must diffuse out. Therefore, it is preferable to have crystalline solids in drug making.&quot; (http://www.utmem.edu/physpharm/.003a.)

 
   

The following model demonstrates the phase transformation of a porous molecular crystal formed by A3B6 under pressure.
When the crystal in the model is compressed, you can see that the orientation of the molecules is disorderly (indicating the amorphous state of the solid), regardless of the temperature. 
1. Take a snapshot of the uncompressed crystal and show in annotation the location of a single unit.  
2. Take a snapshot of the compressed crystal and show with annotation the disorientation of the molecules. 


